basic_information_data.description: Concerns regarding the number and size of bedrooms in a property.
Concerns involving bathroom design, size, and functionality in properties.
Concerns related to identifying and categorizing different types of properties, such as House, Apartment, Studio, Townhouse, Unit, Home & Income, LifeStyle Property and Lifestyle Section.
The legal documentation proving ownership of a property, such as freehold, leasehold, cross lease and Unit.
The strategy used to sell property, including auction, POA, Set date of sale, Asking price, by negotiation, tender, deadline treaty or others.
The total usable surface area within a building, measured in square meters.
The measure of a plot of land surface, measured in square meters.
A set time when a property for sale can be viewed by potential buyers.
The duration that a property has been listed for sale, such as 1 month or 3 months+ and so on.
The decade during which a building was constructed, such as 60s, 70s and so on.
An assessment of property value for taxation purposes, measured in New Zealand dollars.
The increase in property value over time, measured as a percentage.
The materials used for the outside surface of a building.
The materials used to construct the roof of a building.
Automated Valuation Model, an estimate of a property's market value based on data analysis.
Council Valuation, the value of a property according to local government assessments.
Insurance Valuation, the value of a property for insurance purposes.
Land Valuation, the value of the land component of a property.
Real estate agent's estimate of the selling price of the property, measured in New Zealand dollars.
Official permission required to build new structures or alter existing ones.
The date on which a property sale is finalized and ownership is transferred.
An estimate of how much a property could be rented for.
A formal description of a property that identifies it for legal purposes.
A document that proves ownership of a property.
The record of past transactions involving a particular property.
The median Automated Valuation Model value for properties in a suburb.
The change in the median AVM value for a suburb over a period of time.
The median price of rent for properties in an area per month.
The median price of rent for properties in an area per quarter.
The median price of rent for properties in an area per year.
A detailed narrative or summary of a property's characteristics, features, and conditions.
Lines on a map which indicate elevation and the shape of the land.
A person who acts on behalf of another, in particular a real estate agent who arranges the selling, renting, or management of properties.

gis_information_data.description: A designated area where a bus stops for passengers to board or alight.
A designated area set aside for a specific purpose, such as green space, community use, or wildlife conservation.
Areas designated for purchasing goods, such as malls or shopping centers.
A constructed basin filled with water for swimming or leisure activities.
A theatre where movies are shown for public entertainment.
An institution providing medical and surgical treatment and nursing care for the sick or injured.
A building where police officers work and detain people.
Stations where fuel for vehicles is sold.
The number of buildings in a given area.
Government-provided housing for individuals with low to moderate incomes.
The predominant ethnic groups living in a neighborhood.
A terminal where trains load or unload passengers or goods.
A terminal where ferries load or unload passengers or vehicles.
An area of land adjacent to a river which is subject to flooding.
Areas that are susceptible to flooding.
Areas that are affected by flooding, often requiring special insurance or building regulations.
The path that water takes during flooding.
Legislation for the division of an area into zones in which certain land uses are permitted or prohibited.
The designated area or district that determines the schools which residents' children are eligible to attend, significantly affecting property values.
Pipes that carry away sewage or liquid waste.
Pipes designed to carry rainwater away from urban areas.
Pipes that carry drinking water to homes and businesses.
An establishment serving alcoholic beverages.
An establishment serving coffee, drinks, and light meals.
A business that prepares and serves food and drinks to customers.
The number of people living per unit of area, such as per square mile or square kilometer.
A facility equipped for physical exercise and fitness activities.
A place where prescription drugs are dispensed and medical advice is offered.
The varying ages of residents in a property area, influencing housing demand and neighborhood characteristics.
The varying income levels of residents in an area, affecting property prices and market dynamics.
The spread of property ownership types and patterns within a specific area.
The typical duration homeowners reside in their property before moving.
The variety of job types held by residents in a specific area, influencing community composition and housing needs.
The use or inhabitance of a property or space, often in terms of its capacity or number of occupants.

image_information_data.description: A barrier, railing, or other upright structure enclosing an area, typically outdoors, for security or privacy.
Mainly refer to whether there are large trees in the property’s yard.
Mainly refers to whether there is lawn inside the property’s yard.
A property with interior fillers containing asbestos is considered a bad property.
Mainly refers to the decoration style of the house.
Mainly refers to whether there is a slope before and after the property, and whether it is located at the top or bottom of the slope.
A short private road from the street to a house or garage, used by people who are driving to the house.
A bathroom or toilet that is directly connected to a bedroom.
A room in a house where clothes are washed and dried.
A closet or a small room attached to a bedroom used for clothes storage.
A shelter for a car consisting of a roof supported on posts, built beside a house.
The color on the outside of a property.
The color on the inside of a property.
A vertical channel or pipe which conducts smoke and combustion gases up from a fire or furnace and typically through the roof of a building.w
A wall coating made from cement, lime, sand, or gypsum, used to coat walls and ceilings.
A building or indoor area for parking or storing motor vehicles.
The space or features within a property designed to store goods and items.
A division of a larger area, typically for administrative purposes within property development.
A feature of a property that includes a view of the sea.
A feature of a property that includes a view of mountains.
A feature of a property that includes a view of a cityscape.

invisible_information_data.description: A sum of money borrowed from a financial institution to purchase a house.
An attribute of a property indicating that it has features suitable for children
Refers to a living space that is designed to accommodate a family.
Suitability of a property for older individuals, possibly with accessibility features.
The location of the property makes it difficult for outsiders to notice what is going on inside.
The condition of being protected from or unlikely to cause danger, risk, or injury within a property.
The property is pet-friendly and has living space for pets.
